This study explored STEM students' understanding and internalization of growth mindset (GM) during a multi-tiered, multi-year, growth mindset intervention. Aggregate qualitative data were collected from three student cohorts (totaling 30 students) over four years. This poster introduces results including three distinct and emergent themes related to how students across cohorts understood and internalized a growth mindset. Through thematic analysis of cohort focus group transcripts and individual written responses to focus group questions, we report on the three distinct themes of internalizing GM: (a) Conceptual Awareness where students described GM as an abstract concept, (b) Personalization where students described personal and individual experiences of GM, and (c) Integration into Self where students relayed language indicating deep embedding of GM in their identity and behaviors. These themes provide an analytical lens for studying the internalization of GM. Taken together the themes potentially delineate a trajectory of GM development which can be a model for intervention design and assessing impact.